.TH "nilfs_bmap_assign" 9 "nilfs_bmap_assign" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
nilfs_bmap_assign \- assign a new block number to a block
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" nilfs_bmap_assign
.BI "(struct nilfs_bmap *bmap "  ","
.BI "struct buffer_head **bh "  ","
.BI "unsigned long blocknr "  ","
.BI "union nilfs_binfo *binfo "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "bmap" 12
bmap
.IP "bh" 12
pointer to buffer head
.IP "blocknr" 12
block number
.IP "binfo" 12
block information
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
\fBnilfs_bmap_assign\fP assigns the block number \fIblocknr\fP to the
buffer specified by \fIbh\fP.

Return Value: On success, 0 is returned and the buffer head of a newly
create buffer and the block information associated with the buffer are
stored in the place pointed by \fIbh\fP and \fIbinfo\fP, respectively. On error, one
of the following negative error codes is returned.

-EIO - I/O error.

-ENOMEM - Insufficient amount of memory available.
